text: I thought they would be running out of ideas for Bourne in terms of character arcs. Damon himself said after Ultimatum that the character constantly searching for answers about his past was wearing a bit thin.  However, it seems the new angle is he joined because of a lie & that the government/system is continuing to be corrupt & he wants to break it. His motivation now seems to be instead of hitting back at people going after him or looking for answers, he knows the whole system is corrupt no matter who's in charge, even if good people like Landy are there, the corrupt people will just work around her & those like her. This time, he wants more than personal revenge vs Conklin or Vosen or hoping Congressional hearings with Landy with fix it. Bourne seems to be thinking it has to smashed, the entire system.   Could be interesting. Put it this way, I have more faith in this story arc than Renner in Legacy searching for his fucking pills out in Asia.

text: A quote from Matt Damon in 2007 "I think in terms of another one, the story of this guy's search for his identity is over, because he's got all the answers, so there's no way we can trot out the same character, and so much of what makes him interesting is that internal struggle that was happening for him, am I a good guy, am I a bad guy, what is the secret behind my identity, what am I blocking out, why am I remembering these disturbing images? So all of that internal propulsive mechanism that drives the character is not there, so if there was to be another one then it would have to be a complete reconfiguration, you know, where do you go from there? For me I kind of feel like the story that we set out to tell is has now been told. I love the character, and if Paul Greengrass calls me in ten years and says, 'Now we can do it, because it's been ten years and I have a way to bring him back,' then there's a world in which I can go, 'Yeah, absolutely.' We could get the band back together if there was a great idea behind it, but in terms of now and this story, that part‚Äîthe story's been told..."

text: I loved it, and I love how the critics didn't get it, just like they didn't get the last three. This is the essential post-WWII and post-Cold War story of the American Patriot. Do we embrace our government above and beyond our love of the principles on which our Republic was founded in a world that has become hostile to us? Is patriotism loyalty to government and the security it provides, or love of the freedom and equality and the supremacy of conscience that makes us American?  The last three films were focused on Jason Bourne's odyssey of discovering who he was and why he became Jason Bourne. But this film is about who Jason Bourne is at heart, which drives him to do what he does. The one and only time we see him show who he is after Marie's death is in this film, in the street in Athens with Nicky, when he has someone else to protect. It also points to something unique about what an American Patriot is - someone who always seeks to do what is right, because that is at the core of the American values of freedom and equality of the individual.

text: Spoiler Free opinion from somebody who loved the original trilogy:  1. Alicia Vikander is ridiculously good looking. Almost to the point, I'd watch most films just to see her face on screen, because it has some sort of magical effect. 2. Matt Damon is Matt Damon. He always has the same presence and he's a good actor. 3. There seems to be an acting problem in this. A lot of the actors, even some of the main ones, just kept slipping up on their accents. Almost to the point it's very cringe. Some lines, you'll be like.. HOLD UP.. she/he's gone from French, to British to American all in one dialogue. 4. The writing is not anywhere near as good as the first three, and is let down by some silly plot lines, that if better written and structured, could have saved it a bit.  5. Julia Stiles (Nicky in the films) is useless in this film, so if you're a fan of her or she's a reason why you're going. I wouldn't get your hopes up. Her moments are also made worse by the fact her acting in this is god awful for some reason.  Overall. It has some sense of the trilogy and Matt Damon obviously, and isn't too bad of a film. But don't expect it to be like its predecessors. Good action, unrealistic-stupid-albeit still pretty entertaining hacking scenes, and awful acting in some places - saved by the nostalgia, Alicia and Matt.   Worth the money for a film fan.

text: Basically one over the top implausible action vignette  after another minus any real character development or plot. We learn one thing about Jason regarding his father, and nothing else. Even a top actor like Tommy Lee Jones couldn't save this one as it seemed he was phoning in his part for the paycheck. Only bright spot is Heather Lee (Alicia Vikander) doing a passable job of her part, but willing to help Bourne to escape in various close calls and get her boss killed, seemingly, because she wants his job. Other than some well done action scenes, this was a disappointing addition to the Bourne franchise. The whole side show of the obvious Face Book work with the CIA to spy on everyone all the time was a poor attempt at some modern relevance. Watch the trailer and you have seen the movie.  C-

text: The first Bourne movie was actually a TV movie made in 1988 with Richard Chamberlain and Jaclyn Smith with the title The Bourne Identity. Not many watched this movie at the time but I did and I was blown away with the story and the acting (compared to other 80's TV crime cliches). Then in 2002 they made a remake with Matt Damon and Franka Potente. Wasn't too bad but there was no chemistry between Matt and Franka and Matt just didn't have a face for the character. He looked too young and too boyish. Disappointed but watchable. And then came a disaster sequel and the rest not much better. Two things are bad in all sequels. Story and directing! Story becomes so complicated , so technical and so detailed that before the half time you don't care any more. It is just a moving picture. And then the last nail in the coffin is the moving picture or moving camera or better yet shaking camera. And this is because director of all 3 sequels to Matts' series is Paul Greengrass! It is not only shaking camera but also zoom in and on the top of that cuts. Just take any 15 minutes of the movie and don't watch the movie but just directing and you will see. Totally unnecessary closeups, if action scene you have closeups AND shaking camera but also lots of cuts. When the Supremacy was made that was something new in directing. Like a fresh thing. Like enhancing the action, make it more life like feeling. And much cheaper to make. When you shake the camera in closeup you don't see much and when you do cuts every second you don't really see anything properly. You don't have to care of many expensive details of surrounding for the same scene shot normally from the distance with static camera and cuts are then too obvoius. So when the Ultimatum came out and I saw Pauls' name as a director I was reluctant to watch but I hoped he has probably grown out of this CSC directing (Closeup-Shake_Cut). No. Maybe he has grown out of CSC but then must be the cheap price tag that forced him to stick to CSC. When the Jason came out and I saw Pauls' name again I didn't watch the movie at all. Last night my friend got me a BD disk as a present and it was Jason Bourne. I like Vikander so I tought I will just watch her in the movie but after a few actions scenes I just walked away. It is a shame as Matt now older looks closer to the Bourne character and being beefed up and well trained in combat moves, Bourne franchise could have a watchable future. For me at least.

text: Ultimately the most underrated movie of 2016 and one of the most underrated action movies out there, I had only 1 problem with it - the second storyline about that hacker guy was unnecessary. This is the darkest of the Bourne films, and definitely the most morally ambiguous one yet. Bourne here is no more trying to expose government or find the truth, he's here to kill, to get his revenge for Nicky and his father. And in the end he actually does something he constantly tries to avoid - murders the Asset by hunting him down. There's also an ambiguity in his motives - does he want to go back to work for government, is peace no more a solution for him, is he mentally unable to live normal life? And I love that they don't answer these questions, they leave it ambiguous and let viewer think. Amazing film.
